Would you say that method of 'idealization' you described is a good example of how to go about bringing characters closer together?
It is in Roo'd. That aside, when a person is infatuated with another, when he (or she) wants the attention of someone or a group, or when said person is involved with a partner but feels a sense of guilt due to some (often social) element of one-sidedness favoring him (or her), then an emotional condition is established that may impel some change in that individual's character. In literature, that change is usually something like overcoming some unhealthy obstacle, or improving in some way. If the protagonist has an ally (such as the story's waifur), then it might be something that couldn't be accomplished alone, either because the impetus didn't exist beforehand (meet waifur > recognize negative trait through interaction > desire for waifur begets reflection > relinquish, resolve, and/or recompense) or because the protagonist is incapable without aid (physical or emotional). Relinquishing the obstacle may entail overcoming a negative trait, eg alcoholism, fear of change(!), or crippling anxiety. Resolution is meeting a long term goal, or completing something; it's symbolic of the protagonist's change in constitution, of his or her transformation. Recompense is making amends, fixing something that's been broken.
